SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Mar 15 in the evening, patient developed left sided numbness initially in the chest, and then woke up the morning of Mar 16 with numbness on the left side of her face, left arm, and left leg. She also complained of a frontal headache that felt like a sinus infection. She went to the ER at 10am at Hospital. CT brain and CT angio head/neck were negative. MRI  brain w/o contrast showed no stroke and MRI cervical w/o contrast showed mild cervical arthrosis. She had gradual improvement in her numbness. ECHO showed mild LVH, no shunt or PFO. She was started on lisinopril due to mildly elevated blood pressures during this admission- new diagnosis of hypertension.  After discharge she continued to have episodes of left sided numbness and blurry vision nearly every day until she presented to my clinic to establish care on 04/22. At that time she was experiencing numbness on the left side of her face in a V2 distribution. She was sent to the ER at Medical Center and was admitted 4/22- 4/24. CT head was negative. Symptoms resolved after this hospitalization. MRI/MRV was ordered outpatient and performed 05/04.  MRV showed Right transverse venous sinus filling defect probable thrombus, nonocclusive. She was started on Pradaxa 05/05 and has not had any neurologic symptoms since.
LAB_DATA: brain MRI/MRV 05/04: 1. Minimal white matter changes and small vessel disease cribriform  pattern in the basal ganglia. There is no acute infarct. 2. Right transverse venous sinus filling defect probable thrombus,  nonocclusive. Hypoplastic left transverse sinus appears to be  anatomic. 3. Moderate hyperostosis frontalis.
PRIOR_VAX: She reported she can't get flu shots, but did not elaborate

Child screamed in pure panic and pain and ran back and forth like he was on fire a few hours after the vaccines were administered. This last for 45 minutes. Over the course of the next days and weeks he verbally regressed, started hand flapping gestures, and had staring episodes. He developed the symptoms of measles the following week (rash, fever) and then almost 2 weeks  after that he developed the rubella rash and fever. Doctors office confirmed both and they recommended he be seen by an immunologist to test for titers and for immune deficiency issues. Child experienced delayed speech and later developed an autoimmune neurological disorder, plus Tourettes , ADHD,  OCD, anxiety disorder, and depression. Doctors have since stated he likely experienced brain inflammation from the two shots given at once and it has disrupted his immune system so that he has developed an inflammatory immune disorder.
LAB_DATA: Titers tested two months after initial incident. Showed he did not develop immunity to one or two of the components of the MMR or DTaP.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: April 14:  First COVID dose; Upon receiving the shot, my face got hot and flushed.  I felt strange in the head like brain fog, not sharp. This lasted a few hours.  My arm was sore and I experienced fatigue, but all of that seemed relatively normal.  Soreness went away over the next couple of days. April 21:  Day 8; This evening I started feeling a tightness in my chest that felt like what I imagine heartburn feels like, as if something was stuck deep in my esophagus and every time it squeezed I felt pain.  It was painful to take a big breath, I got painful hiccups frequently but not long lasting, and occasional painful twinges like a quick squeeze. April 22:  Day 9; I woke up with a really sore front of the neck, like I had frontal whiplash.  It was painful to move too much, to cough, sneeze, swallow, hiccup. Also got a sensation off and on in my left arm like it was buzzing with alcohol, and occasional twinges of pain or a general light ache. Still had the chest tightness, off and on.  Some days it would last a full day, others it seemed to just act up lightly a few times throughout the day. These symptoms went away by April 24 or 25. April 28:  Day 15 Woke up throughout the night with a severely itchy inner ear (left ear -- same side as injection site). Also the left side of my neck was very itchy and swollen up by my jaw.  Swollen lymph node as well.  The neck muscles on the left side were also sore. My head felt hot to the touch, as if it had a rash. My chest starting hurting again like before, but not as badly (hiccups, big breaths were painful and restricted).  Got the left arm twinges, too, but not as bad. The itchy inner ear lasted two full days, waking me up throughout the night two nights in a row. April 30:  Day 17; I went to urgent care and got an EKG, chest x-ray, and blood tests done.  All results were normal.  The doctor said my ear was red inside and that it must be an ear infection (caused by unknown reasons).  There was no visible rash on the outside (no shingles present).  She prescribed antibiotics, which I planned to fill, but the next day the itching was gone on its own, so I did not take the antibiotics. She had no thoughts on explanation for the other symptoms. May 5:  Day 22; Chest tightness is back, with hiccups.  Front of neck is a little sore, but not as bad as before.  My headache got much worse. May 6:  Day 23; Woke up with a cold (I think):  headache still really bad, sore throat, hot feeling in my head, a little congested, and a little bit of a runny nose.  Stayed home from work, feeling sick.  Still have the chest tightness throughout the day.
LAB_DATA: April 30:  EKG, Chest X-ray, and bloodwork done.  All results normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Please see attached file. Physician Addendum, Specialty: Internal Medicine Cardiovascular Disease, Date of Service: 5/4/2021 10:08 AM, INPATIENT DISCHARGE SUMMARY, Admission Date: 5/3/2021, Discharge Date: 5/4/2021, HOSPITAL SUMMARY, Discharge Diagnosis, Principal Problem: Other acute myocarditis, Active Problems: Chest pain, Tobacco use, Resolved Problems: * No resolved hospital problems. * Reason for Hospitalization, Acute myocarditis after COVID vaccination, Hospital Course - Patient is a very pleasant 20-year-old man without prior medical history who was transferred here from emergency department for further management of chest pain. Patient received his second COVID-19 vaccination on Friday, April 30, 2021 (Pfizer). Later in the evening on Friday, he developed constitutional symptoms, including fever/chills/sweats as well as severe back pain. These symptoms subsided by the following morning but later in the day on May 1, 2021, he developed significant substernal chest pain. The chest pain persisted throughout the weekend. It was worse when he took a deep breath in and also had a positional component. He identified no other aggravating or alleviating factors. When his pain had not resolved, he presented to the emergency department early in the morning on May 3, 2021. On arrival to the outside hospital emergency department, his electrocardiogram was unremarkable, aside from early repolarization abnormality. His troponin was significantly elevated to 7.3. His COVID test was negative. All other lab work was unremarkable, including an undetectable D-dimer. He was transferred here for further management of chest pain and troponin elevation. On arrival here, we completed a CT coronary angiogram, which showed no evidence for coronary stenosis and normal origin of the coronary arteries from the aortic root. An echocardiogram showed preserved left ventricular systolic function and no valvular heart disease. It was, overall, an unremarkable echocardiogram. His troponin was trended and peaked at 7.3. A follow-up troponin after that was 6.4. His presentation is presumed to be related to acute myocarditis secondary to the COVID vaccination. We are obtaining a cardiac MRI as an outpatient on May 4, 2021 (the day after discharge). He will be provided with a one-month supply of colchicine, which he will take daily. We attempted to start him on both Toprol XL and losartan, but we had to discontinue the Toprol XL due to bradycardia (heart rates in the 40-to-50 beats per minute range, increasing only up to 60 beats per minute with activity). He will, therefore, be discharged only on losartan. We will plan to obtain a repeat cardiac MRI in 3-6 months. If that study is favorable, the losartan could be discontinued. Finally, patient had a trip planned with his family to celebrate his 21st birthday in the near future. This trip would obviously involve heavy alcohol consumption. Because alcohol is a cardiotoxin, I advised against such a trip until he has more time to recover from his myocarditis (I also reminded him that heavy alcohol consumption in general is not advised). I provided him a letter that they can use as they cancel their travel plans and seek reimbursement. 04/26/2021 got the shot. An hour later, I had shortness of breath. Kept persisting throughout the week and worsened. On sunday, 05/02/2021 between the hours of 12AM to 2AM, my shortness of breath got worse to the point where I could not breathe. In general, I felt my back and chest tighten. I could only breathe (faintly) to survive. If I took any deeper breaths, my back and chest would hurt even more. As time progressed, My right neck got stiff. Then right my jaw got stiff. Then the right side of my head got stiff. Eventually, the whole right side of my body was numb -- I could move it still but it was still numb and stiff. This happened simultaneously with the breathing issues. This entire time, my whole was tensing, it felt like I could feel my veins while it rushed blood. It was terrible. I thought I was going to die. I did not know which breath would be my last, because every breath got worse and worse. I went to sleep around 2AM and I would periodically wake up. When I'd wake, the pain still persisted. It never went away.  Eventually I got up to go to work around 8AM, the right side of my body wasn't as numb and the breathing wasn't as bad, but you could still tell there was an issue. This issue persisted throughout the day. As of now, these issues are not as persistent, but at least once a day, I still feel the effect. It sucks. A nurse called me (working at the urgent care I gave information about) , on 05/03/2021 saying if I was going to see a primary doctor. I told her that I have an appointment with one on 05/10/2021.  She said that though they called me on 05/02/2021 towards the end of the day and told me everything was fine, that they looked a little deeper and realized that the shape of my cells were weird and that when I go to my primary doctor, they'd be able to access my information.  This is of a complete shock because the shape of my cells were never weird before. This happened as a result of the covid-19 vaccine. This is reaction must be put into the VAERS system.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the first dose on 4/1/21 Lot# ER8733, I had light spotting for 2 days.  Second dose given 04/23/21 and by 04/28/2021 I started bleeding again And by the second day I was soaking through pads and huge clots were coming out. This has never happened to me before.  After 7 days of bleeding heavily I woke up on May 5th at 4:00 a.m. with intense abdominal cramping The only way I can describe was labor. I felt back labor, pelvic pressure, frequent urination and intense pain. I reached out to my gynecologist And he immediately told me to remove my estrogen patch and later that morning he started me on progesterone treatment for 10 days to stop the bleeding. After 7 hours of pain on May 5th, I went to the emergency department and an ultrasound revealed a blood clot. From ultrasound results "there is a complex area in the area of the cervix measuring 5.7 x 3.6 x 2.6 cm."   After several hours I was released from the emergency room taking toradol for pain. That evening I passed a huge blood clot!  I'm very grateful it was where it was and I could expel it.  But there's no doubt the second vaccine caused this issue that has never happened to me before. I still get my periods though irregular and very light. So this event was highly unusual and very painful

She took the first shot and she wanted to say a day or so after that she got up and did some things around the house and she went to the cloth store. She clarified that she went to the fabric store and came out she had a jittery feeling. Then she began to feel woozy and stated she may need to eat. She drove up to by (withheld) and there was a cookout restaurant in the same vicinity as (withheld). When she went to turn into the lot, she was "shaky" and pulled into the parking space. She added that the best thing is for her to go home. She didn't want to take the interstate and went to the back way just in case something happened. She went home and it was approximately 10 miles away. When she got home, she felt even weaker. Her husband was outside because he fishes and was working on his boat. She told him that she doesn't feel well and was shaky. He told her to go in the house and he would come in. She went in through the basement and when she got to the step her foot wouldn't come up, so she crawled up the steps. When her husband came in, she went into a seizure and had no control. She could hear her husband speaking but couldn't speak so he called. They told him to give her four 81 mg of aspirin. So, he gave her some aspirin. She could hear them when they came in to get her, but she couldn't respond. They took her to the hospital. At the hospital they did two CAT scans and another unspecified test. The patient added that she was concerned because she is a very active person, and this is not her normal talk. Before the shot she did a lot of sewing and that's her business. But a few days after the shot she began to have a lot of seizures and went to the hospital. And when she came home it continued. Before she left the hospital, she had not spoken to anyone. When her husband came in, she couldn't get her words out. It has left her with a stutter, and she decided to go to speech therapy. She went in and a few days it seemed like it had helped. The patient further stated that she is not getting back to normal and needs a walker or cane and she's 68 and healthy. The outcome of events was unknown. The patient had no other prior vaccinations (within 4 weeks) of the COVID vaccine. Ongoing concomitant medications included olmesartan for blood pressure, duloxetine for nerve pain, omeprazole for GERD, famotidine for GERD; all taken for years, meloxicam for sciatica taken for 2 months and ongoing and doxycycline from 16Apr2021 and ongoing for tick bite (reported that she kept forgetting to take it). The patient previously received the first dose of BNT162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 mRNA VACCINE, Lot Number: ER8727) on 28Mar2021 at 12:00 in the left arm as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. That dose went in the deltoid and she had no issues. Then she received the second dose on 18Apr2021 at 12:15 in the left arm. She believes it was administered in the soft tissue behind the deltoid. She noticed the person who gave the injection went behind the muscle toward the back of the arm. The next day after the second dose, she felt fine. Then the second morning it felt as if her shoulder was dislocated; and her breast is hard and painful; and she can't breath. She called her doctor who said that was not a common side effect but she stated she knows it is a side effect. The doctor recommended she go to the ER but patient didn't want to go. She added that she put up with the pain all morning and thought maybe she was working herself up so she took one half of a Xanax to calm down, to see if it was just anxiety but the shortness of breath and pain were still there. She reported she was continuing to feel all of these effects at the same level. She doesn't want to go to the ER because of the expense. The shoulder pain was going down her back to the trapezius. She clarified that she can move her shoulder and her arm, but the pain was so breathtaking that she doesn't move it and she has her arm in a sling. There were no relevant tests performed. The clinical outcome of the events right breast pain, breast is hard, shoulder pain, shoulder pain going down her back, shortness of breath, can't move shoulder/arm/ shoulder is immobile, and anxiety was not recovered. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had COVID-19 vaccine Sunday morning.  I noticed fecal impaction Tuesday morning when I tried to use the bathroom .  It did not respond to stool softener (Docusate sodium 100mg) 4 pills a day that I self administered Tuesday and Wednesday.  I sought medical treatment with gastroenterologist Thursday morning.  The NP told me to administer fleet enemas at home .  I self-administered two enemas Thursday morning and evening.   Now, I am having normal bowel function Friday morning.   I believe this event is related to the COVID-19 vaccine because nothing else in my habits or diet was different at this time.  For years prior to this event I had no constipation.  I have regular bowel movements every morning after I drink some caffeine.  I am physically active and eat lots of fiber.  I never use laxatives prior to this event.  On Sunday after I got the vaccine I worked in the garden for several hours.  I felt good while I was working.    But it was in the high 80s and I was in the sun.  This could have caused some dehydration, but I felt fine Sunday night.  Monday I was fatigued which I attributed to the vaccine and I took two advil.  I know advil can be constipating but I only took 2 pills Monday and I commonly take more around my period and have normal bowel function.   Tuesday, I felt fine except for the fecal impaction.   I ate normally Sunday and Monday including lots of vegetables.

Got covid vaccine, had 2nd dose on March 3rd.  Had about 2 days of fevers, aches, night sweats and fatigue.  About 1 1/2 weeks after the dose, he started to get significant fatigue.  He started to sleep poorly.  He developed arthralgias described as bilateral, distal joints (hip down, wrists mainly).  He developed tingling sensations in his arms and legs.  He has had mental fog.  He had some HA and eye pain.  His PCP sent him to the ED for evaluation.  He was evaluated by neuro consult on 4/4, had an LP.  THe LP only showed some elevated protein (somewhat traumatic tap based on 10 RBC in tube 4).  MRI brain, cervical/thoracic spine was unremarkable.  He was dx w/ possible post-infectious polyneurophathy, and suggested f/u w/ neuro clinic for further eval.  Pt reports his paresthesias lasted 2 days and has since resolved.  He has not been seen by outpatient neuro clinic yet.  He did have a post LP HA which he returned to the ED for.  He reports that the HA has resolved.   In the past 2-3 days he has had felt less fatigue.  He still has arthralgias, continuous.  They do not seem to be worse in AM or PM.  He can do most activities and just tired working out this week.  Activity does not seem to make it better or worse.  The joints are not red or swollen but feel "tight".  He has not noticed any fevers but gets occasional nightsweats or sometimes feels flush and measures only a low grade temp that does not last (<100F).  He has had slight decrease in wt but no change in appetite.  No n/v/d.  NO cough, sob, CT/CP, wheezes. No rash. He does have some sinus sx's which he thinks could be c/w seasonal allergies. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my shot at approximately 12:25. Within 5 minutes of my shot I started to feel a bit light headed, hot, having difficulty breathing with my mask on (so I pulled my mask down which helped) and then my heart started racing! After grabbing the attention of the nurses, drinking some water and doing some calming breathing exercises my heart rate went down but not to resting. Upon further investigation through my Apple Watch Heart App, my heart rate had spiked to 141 within those first 5-7 mins of the vaccine. Monitoring myself closely over the next couple of days, my heart rate would have little spikes randomly. I?d be sitting (should be at resting heart rate of 65-70) and I?d spike into the 90?s or 80?s for a few moments then return. The first day it happened about every 20-30 minutes for 3 hours, then tapered off to once every hour or so then the next day every hour or two. By Monday April 26th I felt completely normal and have had no other concerns at this time.
LAB_DATA: I will contact my Dr to report this event and see if she recommends any tests.

Shingles. Around 4/17/2021 saw a couole of bumls that looked like mosquito bite. I scratched and then it eventually turn into a small rash that looked like poison ivy. Took 1000 mg, 3xs/day for 7 days and Tylenol for pain. Pain subsided but had itchy rash along left side. Took claritin for itchiness. Seemed to stablilize. But bister appeared on right shoulder blade.  Continued to take antiviral for a few more days. Also experienced vertigo for a couple of days. Went back to urgent care. Provider said no need to take antivirals anymore and that shingles would run its course. Also said that shingles sometimes appears on other parts of body. Blood pressure taken and normal. Dizziness might be from seasonal allergies. Blisters continued to come out on left side, incl one under left jaw/chin. But bump over next week (wk 3) also appeared on right waist, one on inner ankle, bumps/slight rash on inner right forearm, right neck. Then inner left forearm. I decided to take antiviral early in week (Monday).  Continue to experience itching and take either claritin or benadryl. May visit healthcare provider if worsens or doesn't lessen.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: In the days following the shot, I had the typical symptoms (fever of 101.5, migraine, chills, fatigue, injection site soreness). However, I also had shortness of breath and heart palpitations. My normal 2 mile fast dog walk each night was no longer possible. Even talking on the phone created SOB. This was sudden and unexpected. I went my primary care provider.
LAB_DATA: A week after receiving the shot, I sought out my primary care provider, who did an ECG which showed Right Bundle Branch Block. She then sent me immediately to get a CT scan with dye to check for clots in my lungs. Fortunately, no clots were shown. She also took bloodwork, which showed positive ANAs and specifically, a positive 2.2 score for Scl-70, which is a dangerous autoimmune disease called Systemic Sclerosis. I will see a cardiologist and rheumatologist soon for further testing. All of this is very abrupt. I am also now experiencing acid reflux for the first time ever, which is a common system of Systemic Sclerosis. I should also note that I suspect I may have had COVID in early 2020, as I was low-level sick for about a month and lost my sense of taste and smell. I have since met three other individuals on an online support group for Systemic Sclerosis who have had similar issues - strange and abrupt symptoms directly after their first shot, seeking primary care appointments, and being tested for Scl-70 with positive results. I have encouraged them to report here as well.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D, Iron Supplements, Vitamin C
PRIOR_VAX: In January 2020, I received the flu vaccine. I was sick with flu like symptoms for about 3 days following this.

My 16-year-old daughter, very healthy without any health conditions, got her first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Saturday evening, April 10th, at around 5pm. On Wednesday, she started complaining of shortness of breath, chest pains, which she described as a feeling of someone stubbing her heart. By Thursday, she began blacking out repeatedly throughout the day, each blackout lasting about a minute. These progressed and whenever she blacked out, she would not remember what happened. At first, she and I brushed it off as maybe lack of calcium since she rarely drinks milk. But as they intensified, I began to become more concerned. I told her I cannot leave her by herself in the house as I prepared to go pick up her young siblings from school then schedule an appointment with her doctor. On our way back home, she blacked out again, however, it was for more than a minute. Straight away, I drove to the  ER close by. The doctor came back to inform me that her heartbeat was irregular and concerning based on her age. In that same moment, she began complaining of excessive pain like someone punching her heart out, and then she passed out again. Still with my two other children, the whole ordeal began to frighten them and illicit some heavy tears.  Being that this ER was general admission, the doctors insisted they call in the paramedics to transport her to another ER for children. However, after being transported to the other ER, her condition began to intensify rather quickly and the pediatric doctor at the second ER informed us we would have to be transferred to Childrens intensive care unit where the cardiologists could check her heart, find the ultimate cause, and monitor her closely. In that moment, as a mother, I was speechless and extremely terrified. Seeing my daughter being transferred from ER to ER, made it even tougher on me so much that I could no longer hold myself together. Here she was in terrible pain and being moved around with no clear diagnosis and treatment.  From there on, we spent a couple days in the Cardiac ICU waiting and praying with friends for answers and the best treatment she could get to ease the pain. By about the third day of being in the ICU, the cardiologists informed me, she had Acute Myocarditis. This was so shocking in a sense that both sides of the family have no history of heart issues. Secondly, she is a very healthy child.

A week and a half approximately after the initial vaccination of the J+J covid vaccine I started having a course of strange symptoms. Insomnia, inability to focus on things directly in front of me (a hand in front of my face would go out of focus automatically after a second), blurred vision, short term/long term memory loss, severe emotional issues, difficulty breathing, anxiety. Shortness of breath at a certain point was so bad I thought I was not going to make it. One very troublesome symptom that culminated after weeks of 4 hours of sleep was that my brain started feeling "funny". The best way to describe it was a brain "orgasm" which I have never experienced before. At the same time I experienced dry heaving for several minutes, and severe shortness of breath. After this experience my symptoms gradually improved over the next week or two. Prior to this it felt like my brain was not getting enough oxygen/blood, which could have been feeding my insomnia. When I would try to sleep, I would wake up at 4 am gasping for air, as I felt like my breathing was labored when sleeping. I could not focus on my computer screen to do my job at home. Large amounts of melatonin seemed to help my brain feel better and get some rest. I took hydroxyzine for unrelated reasons prior to the vaccine injection as needed, however not too often. During  March I did not take it, as I had experienced disruptions in circadian rhythm due to the medication. I feel it is possible I had a blood clot that has been described in the news, although now there may be no way to know for sure. I talked with  my primary care physician about this, and he did not think this was the case because I was male. However I have a BMI of 18.7 and some issues females have such as TMJ and inability gain weight/anorexia diagnosis when younger. I also was recently diagnosed with an only recently described actual medical issue called R-CPD, which is the complete inability to burp or belch. I felt like during the time when I experienced the side effects, that this condition was heightened (bloating/loss of appetite). I lost quite a bit of weight during March, I usually weigh 135-140, and was down to 115 at a certain point. I am now back up to 130.   I now take sertraline at 1/4 pill dosage to treat the anxiety I experienced as a result of these symptoms as well as some other personal issues. I experienced severe side effects from the sertraline taking it at full dosage, and still experience some at 1/4 pill dosage.
LAB_DATA: My partner who I am no longer with was a symptomatic covid person, and I was exposed to this person intimately. At the end of January when we broke up, I got nearly a dozen PCR swabs through a pharmacy, all coming back negative, but I was 100% exposed through saliva, bodily fluids, and just sleeping in the same bed. It is possible I had long-covid symptoms prior to receiving the J+J vaccine. I never experienced symptoms, and all tests came back negative, but I did not swab very far up my nose as the pharmacy makes you swab yourself.   In March I went to the emergency room where I was told I had anxiety/depression. I went to an immediate care where I also described sexual dysfunction symptoms, although I have no recollection of this encounter (I received a bill in the mail). I also got at least 3 PCR covid tests in March as I thought I had possibly gotten covid. All turned up negative.
HISTORY: R-CPD, acid reflux, IBS, anorexia (when younger, no longer an issue but difficulty gaining weight)

Patient had an appointment in our office today for Moderna COVID vaccine fist dose. Minutes after administration patient was found to be lethargic. Patient responded slowly to calling his name. Upon touching patients arm, diaphoresis noted. Spouse present who stated patient has vasovagal reactions at times. Vital signs 80/42-112-99% on room air. Patient answered all orientation questions appropriately. Assisted patient to elevate legs, cool cloth applied to forehead and arms. Patient responding verbally and verbalized he was feeling better within a minute of his feet being elevated. Vital signs rechecked, 90/48-52-18-96% on room air. Per patient and spouse, patient has had vagal reactions while moving bowels in the past. Patient reports he has often felt nausea prior to this happening in the past. Patient stood and walked around exam room with supervision, no abnormalities noted. Patient continued to be monitored for a total of 30 minutes. Vital signs rechecked, 116/58-60-16-96% on room air. Per patient he feels "back to normal".   Informed patient that I would be notifying his PCP of this event with the request to add vasovagal episodes to his history to ensure providers are aware of this.    Informed patient with second COVID vaccine dose we would have patient on exam table to ensure we are able to assist with leg elevation in event that this occurs again. Patient and spouse in agreement with plan of care.

I am 62 years old. I received my first Moderna vaccine on 3/3/21.  Very painful, red and swollen at the injection site. One week after the shot  I developed an itchy red and swollen palm on my left hand, shot was in my left arm.  The second shot was 3/31/21. I chose to switch to my right arm due to the reaction to the first shot. On 4/2/21 I had a severe stomach upset which is highly unusual for me. I developed spasms in my throat which traveled down into my side. Very painful. I became nauseous during the night causing me to vomit. Went to the ER in the morning, had an ultrasound to rule out gallbladder problems and was diagnosed with esophageal spasms. First and only time to ever experience this.  Developed an itchy red and swollen palm again, this time in right hand, corresponding with the shot in right arm.  On 4/17/21 I woke up with pain on the right side of my tongue, I thought it was a canker sore. Right half of my tongue started to swell immediately.  I had trouble speaking and speech was slurred. Second trip to ER in two weeks. Very scary. I was given an IV with Benadryl, Prednisone, and Pepcid. Took several hours for swelling to go down.  I have never experienced these symptoms before nor have I had severe reactions to any other vaccinations. I have been in the hospital twice in my 62 years.....37 and 35 years ago to deliver our two sons. I firmly believe that these problems were directly related to the vaccine. I still believe that getting the vaccine is the right thing to do. I am hoping that knowing about my reaction is helpful in some way shape or form.
LAB_DATA: I had several blood tests to rule out serious disease such as Lupis and Hereditary Angiodema

I developed a "blurry spot" (later noted to be a scrotoma) in my vision of my right eye a few days after my vaccine. No pain was associated, just a small spot of blurred/rainbow vision. I did not initially connect it to the vaccine, and do not know for sure if it is connected, but it seems pertinent. I was first seen by my optometrist who did a retina scan and found a retinal hemorrhage. I subsequently saw my PCP, a neurologist and a retina specialist. After more scans, I was diagnosed with Acute nueromacular retinopathy. My doctor, who is a specialist in this specific disorder, noted there had been some connections to this very rare disorder and Covid-19, as well as vaccines. Not a lot is known about this disease, but I did have other potential risk factors, such as being on birth control. Hard to say what actually caused it. But the close connection to the vaccine in timing is suspicious. I am personally curious if there are other documented cases.

The medical investigator was contacted regarding the death of this 80 year old man within hours of receiving his first dose of the Pfizer vaccine for COVID-19. Little information is known about the facility and actual vaccination administered at the time of this report. However, patient was reported by his next-of-kin to be an otherwise healthy 80 year old without COVID-19 symptoms. He did have a tobacco smoking history. By postmortem computed tomography scans, patient was found to have evidence of catastrophic complications of cardiovascular disease, with apparent aortic dissection and large blood collections in the left chest cavity as well as the pericardial sac. In my medical opinion, these findings were most consistent with a complication of his underlying cardiovascular disease.

I felt super cold around 10 pm and at the same time, I had a fever, too. I went to bed early that night (around 10:30 pm) and since I was super cold, I had 3-4 blankets on me when I was on my bed. Suddenly, at 1 am, I woke up due to a very strange noise in my head (a very low-volume noise of knocking on the door every 10 seconds!! I think it was only something in my mind). Since I couldn't sleep because of that low artificial noise, I decided to go to the bathroom at around 1:10 am (My bode was also in lots of pain at that time). When I started to walk, I realized that something is wrong with my body. When I peed and stood up to get back to my bed, I noticed that I'm losing control! Therefore, I hit the bathroom door to wake up my girlfriend, and then I fainted! (I can't remember anything for about 30 seconds here). My girlfriend told me that when I fainted, one of my eyeballs was upward and the other was downward (like zombies!!). She started to freak out and called her mom, but once they started talking, I woke up. My body was soaking wet when I woke up and I was in lots of pain. I asked her to help me to lay down on the ground. After 10 minutes, that my sweats were gone, I started feeling cold and asked her to give me a blanket. I couldn't sleep for about 2-3 hours after I fainted, but I was feeling better (I was much better than the time before fainting). On Monday afternoon, I called the health center and told them my side effects. They strongly recommended visiting ER ASAP since the symptoms that I described were severe side effects of Pfizer. Therefore, I went to ER on Monday (April 26th) to see what?s the issue. Hopefully, after spending 3-4 hours there, and passing some tests, the results did not show anything wrong with my body, but just the side effects of the vaccine.

Before receiving the vaccination the patient mentioned he had a fear of needles.  Patient was asked if he ever fainted after getting a vaccination or injection and patient reported no.   The vaccine was administered to the patient and patient appeared to be fine for the next few minutes after getting vaccinated.  Patient was told he could take a seat in the waiting area and wait until his 15-minutes were up and he could go.  Patient was seated in the waiting area for about a minute but then got up to walk down one of the isles. When walking down the isle patient fainted and collapsed. This occurred approximately 10 minutes or so after he received the vaccine.  Patient was helped to a chair and once seated appeared to shake/convulse (almost like a seizure) for approximately 5-10 seconds before snapping out of it and regaining consciousness.  Afterwards he was alert and talking but didn't remember fainting.  911 was called and he was checked out by paramedics. After observing him for 15 minutes or so and determining his heartrate and blood pressure were normal and he appeared to be ok, the paramedics told him they can take him to the hospital to be evaluated further, or he was free to leave on his own without going to the hospital.  The patient said he felt fine and declined being taken to the hospital. After another 10-15 minutes the patient left under his own power. Patient mentioned he would possibly be calling his physician and alerting them to the episode.
HISTORY: Patient mentioned he had a fear of needles/injections.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is an 85-year-old female with a history of hypothyroidism, hypertension, and osteoarthritis who presented from home complaining of 4 days left shoulder pain that radiates into her left pectoral area.  She states she was vaccinated with the Janssen Covid vaccine on 4/8/21 in her left shoulder and her pain started 4/23/21.  She is not sure if these were related.  It was initially intermittent, sharp, stabbing, however became fairly persistent.  She has noted her blood pressure being elevated.  On my evaluation her blood pressure is 185/64.  Patient states she was recently started on lisinopril for hypertension.  She has not taken her lisinopril yet today. Chest x-ray showed no obvious infiltrates.  Clear lung fields.  Normal cardiac dimensions. EKG shows sinus mechanism with normal axis, intervals, ST segments.  Otherwise normal EKG. D dimer was elevated, and VQ scan was negative for PE. Patient was evaluated by Cardiology who recommended outpatient stress test. Echo showed LVEF 60-65%. Trace aortic valve regurgitation. Mild mitral regurgitation. Mild mitral leaflet calcification is visualized. Trace tricuspid regurgitation. The right ventricular systolic pressure is calculated at 28mmHg. Patient was found to have hyperlipidemia and was started on statin. Her pain resolved on the day of discharge. Her blood pressure was controlled with lisinopril and coreg. She is to follow up with Cardiology and her PCP.

Health concern: Patient came in for his second covid vaccine around 9:35 AM.  Patient was roomed by Medical Assitant (MA). The MA  was administering the vaccine in the deltoid muscle in the left arm when the MA noticed that the vaccine was leaking from the syringe.The MA noticed that more than half of the vaccine was leaking down the patient's arm.  He immediatel reported incident to MA Supervisor. MA supervisor reported incident to the provider NP. The Provider found the guideline on the CDC for this particular incident.  She also called Moderna the manufacturer and they concurred with CDC's the guidelines. The MA's supervisor found that the needle that was used had a manufacturer defect. The needle did not tighten when screwed on the syringe.  The rest of the syringes from that box were examained and found to have a totel of 4 defective syringes.  The needles and syringes are provided by the state Department of Health Services. A new shipment arrives everytime the vaccines are ordered.    After receiving guidance from Moderna and reviewing the CDC guidelines, the patient received a second dose in the deltoid muscle of right arm, administered by a different MA. The lot number and  expiration are the following respecively 021C21A,  10/21/2021. Patient was observed in lobby for 15 minutes with no side effects noticed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the 2nd dose of vaccine, I became very ill and missed 6 days of work. I have never been so cold in my life but I was completely drenched in sweat. After that for probably another 7-10 days I was still more tired than usual, felt a little more winded, and still had an issue with my head I can't really describe. This brings me to the evening of May 2, when I got a fever and chills and sweat all night. May 3, I was exhausted to the point of falling asleep while driving, and my face was on fire. By May 4, I was miserable and left work for a Covid test (which came back negative). The 5th and 6th I continued with the symptoms, the high fever and chills and unable to stay hydrated. 6th I got IV for fluids. All symptoms were very similar to what happened after 2nd vaccine dose.

I was called onto the scene around 1:25pm and was told by the manager on site to help with a patient who was feeling lightheaded. I went with one of the workers in the building who was able to obtain information from the patient that she had a history of epileptic seizures and directed me to the patient with a wheelchair. When I arrived on scene, which was a few hundred yards away in the convention center, there was a bystander there to help the patient and security a few yards away.  I asked the patient how she was feeling and she stated that she was feeling weak and light-headed. I brought her over to a dark lighted area, via wheel chair, 10 yards away and laid her in on the ground to get maximum amount of blood flow to the brain. I was able to get her history, which she did not have allergies, and gave me the the information regarding her seizures that occurred every month to two months. As I asked about her medications for the seizures, first focal epileptic seizure started. The patient was away from all anything that could obstruct her and the seizure lasted for one minute. After this, colleagues and two EMS personnel from the convention center came on scene and the colleague dialed 911 after I stated that the patient had a seizure. The patient recovered, was able to obtain pulse, which was just over 100 bpm, and asked her questions regarding her name, time, place, and event and the patient was able to correctly respond. The patients skin was warm and was only brought to a sitting position when she needed to sip on water. I was able to give information to the dispatch during the call and monitored pulse and breathing. She was willing to go to the hospital when EMS arrived. The second focal epileptic seizure was five to seven minutes after the first one and again lasted for a minute. Again, the patient was alert and oriented to name, time, place and event. The patient was able to give me her ID and as I was getting her pulse and further information, a third focal epileptic seizure took place and this is when the EMS unit came on scene. They were able to take care of the patient and obtain vitals (130/90 blood pressure, just over 100 glucose). The patient was carefully sat up from the ground, laid on the cot, and the EMS unit transported the patient to a hospital. I signed witness to the security as to what happened and actions taken.
OTHER_MEDS: N/A- Was not able to obtain patient information on scene regarding the medications for the epileptic seizures and high blood pressure.
CUR_ILL: Patient stated that they had epileptic seizures once every one to two months
HISTORY: Patient stated that they had high blood pressure on scene.

Then the pain in the nerves started. It is continuous and feels like bugs or bubbles crawling under skin with increased nerve pain that is always there. There are times when it's excruciating pain & other times manageable but it's always there. I can even feel it in my sleep & even dream of sores all over my body. The main area of pain is in the legs but it also affects the entire body as random pain & stabs occur in various areas.

No labs or test have been conducted.
PRIOR_VAX: Small Pox, around 8 years old, very high fever, infected arm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Thursday, 5/6/21, client was to receive his first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT #: EW0167, exp: 8/2021) at approximately 10:30am. RN  administered client's first dose in his left deltoid. Client was observed in the Observation Area for 15 minutes with no adverse effects and left vaccination site with a steady gait at approximately 11:10am. RN finished administering his 6 doses around 11:45am and returned his Participant Form for "Vial 24." RN noticed a duplication in vial number 24 forms. Upon further assessment, RN recognized that she had reconstituted the same Pfizer vial, vial 24, twice with 1.8ml of Normal Saline. Issue was elevated immediately to Clinical Lead who advised to call patient back to receive the proper full dose. Client was called at 1:15pm. RN  apologized and explained to client what happened. Client was understanding and verbalized agreement to come back at 2:30pm. Client received his first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine (LOT #: EW0179, exp: 8/2021) on opposite arm at 2:36pm. Client denied history of severe allergic reactions. Client was observed in Observation Area for 30 minutes. Client was educated by RN on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Client was also encouraged to sign-up on v-safe. Client left vaccination site with a steady gait at approximately 3:06pm.

Took the antiviral the prescribed 7 days.  Have been on Gabapentin since.  Amitriptyline was added recently because the pain continues to not be under control and sleeping is a challenge.  It has been 19 days approximately since symptoms began and 17 days since diagnosis.  I don't know the outcome yet since I still have somewhat of a rash left.  The rash was large and and extended from the top of my tailbone down and out toward my hip down into the top of my thigh.  The antiviral helped in that blisters never really formed, although I do have the burning pain and itching on the rash and also in the nerve following all through the route down into my foot and groin.

Second shot had no instant reaction, injection site just slowly began hurting. An hour later, and very suddenly, brain fog hit me and i lost all short term memory, mid sentence. Similar to what I would consider a form of Alzheimer?s. At the same time I developed a headache, not as severe as the first shot, but I was more exhausted than the first shot. Forming sentences, being able to think was very difficult for 72 hours. I was exhausted, arm hurt. After the 72 hours, I lost my sense to smell. I am in my 96 hour since my second injection and still have no sense of smell. I can taste. Never had a fever but for both shots it felt like it was absorbed by my muscles and was then converted to something else which was then released back into my system. It was like I had sore muscles it was like my muscles became the poison. This effect was grossly more profound  after the second vaccine.  The ability to think was the scariest side effect.

Patient received the COVID vaccine in the RA and immediately complained of the pain and stated she felt dizzy, faint, and lightheaded. She said she thought the needle was still in the arm until she felt the bandaid go on and realized it wasn't. She said she felt nauseous, and slouched down in her seat. I went to get a trash can just in case she got sick and she immediately got out of the chair and said she needed to lie down on the floor. We placed her on the pharmacy floor and she said she was having a hard time breathing and her head "felt funny and weird". I retrieved the EpiPen but she said she never had one and didn't want to get it yet. She was conscious the whole time and appeared to be hyperventilating so we never administered the Epipen. She said her fingers were tingly and requested we call the paramedics so we did. They arrived very timely and took over. They took her BP and it was fine. They asked if she wanted to go to the hospital and she said no. She stated she was starting to feel better, she could breath more easily. She  eventually was able to sit up and the paramedics got her to call her son to come pick her up and the paramedics walked her out of the store to meet him.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was seen at the urgent care clinic on 4/19/2021 having congestion for a couple of days as well as cough, news throat the head and troubles breathing was noted to have normal oxygen saturation and was given an albuterol inhaler and told that she had a virus.  She followed up in the PCP office on 4/21/2021 with worsening troubles breathing and was given Decadron in the office, 4days of prednisone, CXR and labwork.  CXR showed possible reactive airway disease and was to do steroid and continue out albuterol every 4 hours.  Had negative/normal lab work and positive Covid antibodies.  History of Covid 10/2020.  Felt almost completely back to normal by Sunday, her last day of steroids.  On Monday had worsening of her breathing throughout the day, increased troubles breathing again after softball that night.  Albuterol did seem to help up.  Called the office as she woke up Tuesday morning with worsening and would started on Flovent.  With no improvement return to PCP office on 4/29/2020 with marked inspiratory stridor.  Was admitted to the hospital for work-up of return of stridor.  Had a normal chest x-ray and neck/soft tissue x-ray.  With continued troubles breathing and chest pains with decreased heart rate was elected to go to  Hospital where she could have further work-up.  When the ARNP came helicopter, was concerned about her airway and she intubated to fly to hospital.  Was dx there with Sudden Acute Onset of Vocal Cord Dysfunction and is continuing with therapies.
LAB_DATA: 4/21/21 CXR, CBC, CMP, CRP, ESR, TSH, Ft4, covid antibodies. 4/29/21 CXR, neck/soft tissue xray 4/30/21 direct laryngoscopy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient reported that she has known vaso-vagal syncope with shots or blood draws so she was given the shot in the medical tent by nursing staff in supine position. She tolerated well. She was observed x 15 minutes and felt well, however, when she stood up to leave she reported feeling light-headed again. EMS evaluated her and found BP 70/50 and HR in 30s-40s.  BS 111. RR 16. The patient was put back into supine position and reported feeling well after a few minutes. She was able to sit up and drink water and orange juice, however, she continued to have episodes of bradycardia and hypotension. EKGs were performed laying, sitting, and standing. NSR with HR in 60's while laying down but bradycardia with HR 30s-40s when sitting or standing and patient reported feeling light-headed in those positions. She initially refused transfer to the ED for further evaluation but after counseling she did agree and was transferred via ambulance in stable condition.
CUR_ILL: None known but patient does not receive any preventative care

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 36 hours after vaccination, I woke up at 3am with ringing in both ears for the first time in my life.  I've seen two ENTs and a chiropractor. My hearing test was normal and showed no loss of hearing. The ENT said the pressure test was normal.  I have had periods of ear pressure, clogging and the feeling of water in the ears.  Over the past 10 weeks, those specific symptoms have diminished and only now happen a few times a week, but the ringing in the ears persists.  It is constant.  I have gotten more used to it, and there are times when it's louder and times when it's less loud, but I cannot say that it is "disappearing".  The ringing is definitively not resolved.  I have tried prescription nasal spray and allegra, which possibly help. In addition, 13 days after vaccination, I started experience chest tightness, sternum pain, aches and pains throughout my upper body: both arms, back.  The tightness in the chest is exacerbated by exercise. Those symptoms have diminished over time but have not resolved. I have not gone back to exercise. Chest xray was negative and stress test was normal. Transthoracic Echo showed some abnormalities. Blood pressure became elevated post vaccination and remains elevated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 02/27/2021 -received vaccine #1. 03/01/2021 - began to have chest tightness. All through March I felt bad with symptoms of muscle aches, headaches, shortness of breath, loss of appetite, nausea. By the middle of March I felt so bad that on the 17th I had a covid test, which turned out negative. On the 20th I had nausea and vomiting and a fever of 101 to 102 degrees. I received instructions to use ondansetron for the Nausea/vomiting and Tylenol for the fever. On the 22nd I had a virtual with the nurse practitioner; she determined I had a GI virus and was not in need of anything further. I felt better on the 25th & 26th and decided to get vaccine #2 on the 03/27/2021. On the night of the 27th I went to the ER for worsening shortness of breath and chest pain, especially with deep inspiration, and nausea/vomiting. I was admitted to medical center with a (later) diagnosis of Bilateral Pleural Effusion. I was started on antibiotics and received multiple tests including x-rays, blood tests, cardiac function,Ct scan with contrast, images from nuclear med and more. A thoracentesis was done to drain a pocket of fluid in the left lower pleura - 700cc was removed and sent to the lab. Between the blood work and the pleura fluid it was determined that I had Systemic Lupus. I had no other acute s/s of Lupus although the Cutaneous Lupus had been diagnosed for many years.
LAB_DATA: from 03/27/2021 to 04/1/2021 at facility: chest x-rays, CT scan, blood tests, EKG, cardiac function test, thoracentesis, covid test  03/17 and 04/08/2021 Covid tests, 04/09/2021 pulmonary function test

Adverse Event: Syncopal Episode s/p Vaccine Administration  Details: Pt presenting into exam room 1 for Pfizer COVID vaccine dose 1 around 6:20pm. Vaccine was administered into LT deltoid and pt stated that he is known to pass out after vaccines. I advised pt to stay in clinic for 15 mins or more if needed and pt agreed, and I also gave him 2 small bottles of water and highly advised him to drink them while he waited the 15 mins. I asked pt if he wanted to sit in our exam room but declined and stated that he would sit outside in our waiting area. After 5 mins (around 6:25pm), customer came and told us that someone was laying on the floor. Patient was found on other side of wall divider on the LT hand side of our waiting area laying on the LT side of his face and on his stomach. Pt aroused immediately to tactile stimulation and me calling his name. He was oriented X4 and stated that he was okay but wanted to lay on the cool floor for a moment. Pt was cool and clammy to touch and skin color pale pink. No hematomas or lacerations noted to face or head. No seizure activity noted. Stayed on floor for approx 3-4 mins and myself and another person stayed with him. There were 2 other patients present in the waiting room at the time, and the pharmD, also responded to make sure that we did not need any more help. After 3-4 mins of pt resting on floor, he agreed to get up and go into exam room 2 to lay on exam table. Patient said that he knew he was going to pass out because he heard ringing in his ears so he sat on the floor. He said the next thing he knew, I was calling his name and he was laying on the floor. Pt was escorted by me to room 2. AAOx4. V/S taken at that time: BP 120/80 HR 74 RR 16 O2 sats 98%. Skin warm and darker pink. Exam table put in incline position and pt resting there until 6:40p. Drank his 2 small bottles of water that was given to him and was stable upon leaving clinic. Offered to call someone to come get him but pt declined.
PRIOR_VAX: syncopal episodes
